prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: We ask for the coarsest spatial resolution for this detection experiment, most sources should remain basically unresolved. All sources are expected to have CO[5-4] line flux larger than 1 Jy*km/s (see Science Justification). We require a detection with S/N>5 at this level, corresponding to 0.5mJy rms for a linewidth of 400km/s. The coarsest spectral resolution will correspond to some 30-40 km/s, for a 2GHz (2400km/s) bandwidth, and this will be entirely appropriate for this project. We need all 4 basebands. All will be covering the CO[5-4] for a subset of the targets, and the combination of them will be used to measure the continuum. The expected data rate is just 2.2MB/s, well below the limit.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We propose to detect CO[5-4] (and the 520um rest-frame continuum as a bonus) for 127 galaxies at 1.1<z<1.7 in the COSMOS field, selected to have log(LIR/Lsun)>12 (and up to 13.2) measured by Herschel, including similar numbers of main sequence and starburst galaxies. Thanks to our direct detection with IRAM PdBI of CO[5-4] in a small sample of comparable objects, and evidence of a linear LIR to LCO[5-4] relation, we can reliably estimate the required integration time that is of order of 1-2 minutes per galaxy, enough also for continuum detection. We will have measurements of high-J CO[5-4] luminosity, LIR, Mdust and Mgas (from continuum) and of U=LIR/Mdust, equivalent to dust temperature. We will be able to perform an unprecedented investigation into the nature of star formation inside high-redshift galaxies, statistically confirm at z=1.4 the supposed linear relation between LIR and L'CO[5-4] and measure its scatter and systematics for different galaxy types, and explore the correlation between CO excitation and star formation efficiency. With 7.4h of ALMA observing time in Band6 we will obtain the first statistical sample of CO detections in the z~1.4 Universe.
prp:ObsProposal.prp:scientificCategoryString: Cosmology and the High Redshift Universe
